TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Impact of Team Empowerment on Virtual Team Performance: The Moderating Role of Face-to-Face Interaction
AU  - Kirkman, Bradley L.
AU  - Rosen, Benson
AU  - Tesluk, Paul E.
AU  - Gibson, Cristina B.
Y1  - 2004/04/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159571
DO  - 10.5465/20159571
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 175
EP  - 192
VL  - 47
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We investigated the relationship between team empowerment and virtual team performance and the moderating role of the extent of face-to-face interaction using 35 sales and service virtual teams in a high-technology organization. Team empowerment was positively related to two independent assessments of virtual team performance? process improvement and customer satisfaction. Further, the number of face-to-face meetings moderated the relationship between team empowerment and process improvement: team empowerment was a stronger predictor for teams that met face-to-face less, rather than more, frequently.
AB  - We investigated the relationship between team empowerment and virtual team performance and the moderating role of the extent of face-to-face interaction using 35 sales and service virtual teams in a high-technology organization. Team empowerment was positively related to two independent assessments of virtual team performance? process improvement and customer satisfaction. Further, the number of face-to-face meetings moderated the relationship between team empowerment and process improvement: team empowerment was a stronger predictor for teams that met face-to-face less, rather than more, frequently.
