TY  - JOUR
T1  - Earnings Management Following Duality-Creating Successions: Ethnostatistics, Impression Management, and Agency Theory
AU  - Davidson, Wallace N.
AU  - Jiraporn, Pornsit
AU  - Kim, Young Sang
AU  - Nemec, Carol
Y1  - 2004/04/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159577
DO  - 10.5465/20159577
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 267
EP  - 275
VL  - 47
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We explore impression and earnings management via reasoning and methods grounded in ethnostatistics and agency theory. We hypothesized that earnings management occurs more frequently following duality-creating successions than otherwise because CEO-chairs have greater control of the impressions created by their firms' financial reports and are operating under greater expectations of positive results. Using a sample of 173 duality-creating succession announcements and 112 non-duality-creating succession announcements, we obtained empirical results consistent with these predictions.
AB  - We explore impression and earnings management via reasoning and methods grounded in ethnostatistics and agency theory. We hypothesized that earnings management occurs more frequently following duality-creating successions than otherwise because CEO-chairs have greater control of the impressions created by their firms' financial reports and are operating under greater expectations of positive results. Using a sample of 173 duality-creating succession announcements and 112 non-duality-creating succession announcements, we obtained empirical results consistent with these predictions.
