TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is High Employee Turnover Really Harmful? An Empirical Test Using Company Records
AU  - Glebbeek, Arie C.
AU  - Bax, Erik H.
Y1  - 2004/04/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159578
DO  - 10.5465/20159578
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 277
EP  - 286
VL  - 47
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We tested the hypothesis that employee turnover and firm performance have an inverted U-shaped relationship: overly high or low turnover is harmful. Our analysis was based on economic performance data from 110 offices of a temporary employment agency. These offices had high variation in turnover but were otherwise similar, allowing control for important intervening variables. Regression analysis revealed a curvilinear relationship; high turnover was harmful, but the inverted U-shape was not observed with certainty.
AB  - We tested the hypothesis that employee turnover and firm performance have an inverted U-shaped relationship: overly high or low turnover is harmful. Our analysis was based on economic performance data from 110 offices of a temporary employment agency. These offices had high variation in turnover but were otherwise similar, allowing control for important intervening variables. Regression analysis revealed a curvilinear relationship; high turnover was harmful, but the inverted U-shape was not observed with certainty.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/20159578
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/20159578
Y2  - 2026/04/24
